            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this peer to peer loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Peer to peer (P2P) lending platforms usually offer fixed-rate,
                fully amortizing loans with regular payments. This calculator
                models those cash flows from both the borrower and investor
                perspectives, including common platform fees.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                The periodic payment is based on the standard annuity
                (amortizing loan) formula:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1 text-sm"><strong>Payment</strong>:</p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  \( PMT = P \times \dfrac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm mt-2">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li>
                    <strong>P</strong> = loan principal (amount borrowed /
                    invested)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = periodic interest rate (APR ÷ payments
                    per year)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>n</strong> = total number of payments</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Interest, principal and balance</h3>
              <p>For each payment period the calculator computes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest</strong> = previous balance × periodic rate
                </li>
                <li><strong>Principal</strong> = payment − interest − fees</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>New balance</strong> = previous balance − principal
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Platform fees</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Origination fee</strong> – a one-time fee charged at
                  the start as a % of the loan amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Servicing fee</strong> – an ongoing fee charged as a %
                  of each payment (usually to investors).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator shows how these fees change the total cost for
                borrowers and the net return for investors.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Effective annual rate (EAR) and IRR</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>effective annual rate (EAR)</strong> converts the
                nominal APR and payment frequency into a true annualized rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">\( EAR = (1 + \dfrac{APR}{m})^m - 1 \)</p>
                <p class="text-sm mt-1">
                  where <strong>m</strong> is the number of payments per year
                  (12, 26, or 52).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For investors, the calculator also estimates the
                <strong>internal rate of return (IRR)</strong> based on the
                actual cash flows after servicing fees.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for using the P2P loan calculator</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Compare different platforms by adjusting origination and
                  servicing fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Switch between monthly, bi-weekly and weekly payments to see
                  the effect on total interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Turn on extra payments to see how much faster you can pay off
                  the loan and how much interest you save.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Export the amortization schedule to CSV if you want to run
                  your own analysis or graphs.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this calculator specific to one P2P platform?</h3>
              <p>
                No. It is platform-agnostic. As long as the loan uses a fixed
                interest rate and regular amortizing payments, you can
                approximate it by entering the correct APR, term, payment
                frequency and fees.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I model multiple P2P loans at once?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool models one loan at a time. To approximate a
                diversified portfolio, you can enter the
                <em>average</em> rate, term and fees, or export several
                schedules and combine them in a spreadsheet.
              </p>

              <h3>Does the calculator include taxes or defaults?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Taxes, defaults and recoveries vary by country and platform.
                The results assume all payments are made on time. Investors
                should treat the IRR as a
                <em>before-tax, before-default</em> estimate.
              </p>
            </section>
